🎓 TEACHING CAPTURE — MILESTONE 2 (Scene System + Engine Refactor)

Now the project stops being a demo… and becomes a system.

🎯 Learning Objectives

Students should understand:

what an Engine is and why it exists
how to separate orchestration from behavior
how a Scene system structures a game
how to implement a scene lifecycle
how to safely refactor code into a cleaner architecture
how input triggers state transitions
🧱 Lecture Outline
1. The Problem: “Who’s in Charge?”

Start with this question:

“Right now… who is actually running the game?”

Students will realize:

main.ts is doing too much
logic is scattered
there is no clear “owner”

💬 Key line:

“Every non-trivial system needs a conductor.”

2. Introducing the Engine

Explain:

Engine = central coordinator

Responsibilities:

owns the game loop
owns the canvas and context
tracks current scene
controls transitions

💬 Analogy:

“The Engine is the conductor. It doesn’t play instruments—it tells everything when to play.”

3. Refactoring the Game Loop

Show:

👉 loop in main.ts → moved into Engine.ts

Explain:

why this improves structure
why centralizing timing matters

💬 Key line:

“Control belongs in one place.”

4. Scene System — The Big Idea

Define:

A Scene = a self-contained part of the game

Examples:

title screen
gameplay
pause menu

💬 Key line:

“A game is just a sequence of scenes.”

5. Scene Base Class (Contract)

Introduce:

update(dt)
render(ctx)
onEnter()
onExit()

Explain:

This is not just code… it’s a contract

💬 Analogy:

“Every scene agrees to follow the same rules, even if they behave differently.”

6. Scene Lifecycle

Walk through:

onEnter()
repeated update()
repeated render()
onExit()

💬 Key line:

“Scenes don’t just exist—they transition.”

7. Scene Switching

Show:

Engine.setScene()
old scene exits
new scene enters

Explain:

This is a state transition system

💬 Key line:

“This is your first real state machine.”

8. Input Triggers Behavior

Show:

key press in TitleScene
triggers transition to PlayScene

Explain:

input → decision → state change

💬 Key line:

“Input doesn’t just do things—it changes what system is active.”

9. Clean Separation of Concerns

Reinforce:

Engine → orchestration
Scene → behavior
Systems → support (future milestones)

💬 Key line:

“Structure prevents chaos.”

10. Architecture Walkthrough

Walk through:

main.ts (bootstrap only)
Engine.ts (runtime control)
Scene.ts (contract)
TitleScene.ts
PlayScene.ts

This is a beautiful moment to zoom out.

🎥 Live Coding Plan

This one is really strong live.

Suggested flow:

Show messy loop in main.ts
Move loop into Engine.ts
Run → verify nothing broke
Add Scene base class
Add currentScene
Add TitleScene
Add PlayScene
Wire scene switching (Enter key)
Run → transition works

👉 Students LOVE seeing the transition happen live

🧪 Student Exercises
Easy
change title text
change background colors
Medium
change key from Enter → Space
add a second message in PlayScene
Stretch
